<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-267-184  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 267 184.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  Feb 19 1990 v4 n7 p14(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>New standards to help ensure voting accuracy. (The FederalElection Commission's 186-page standard for voting automation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Smithmidford, Robert.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Federal Election Commission (FEC) releases a 186-page standardfor voting automation for states and localities after six years ofdevelopment work and 10 rounds of comment from the public.andP;  Addedsince the most recent draft are accuracy rates, a time clockrequirement supporting a dated audit trail and specificationsremoving limitations for direct electronic recording systems.andP;  Theoverall quality of data read-write and transfer quality statusmust be monitored by the software, which must also check thenumber and types of errors and assure that they are corrected.andO;Such high-level structured programming languages as C, Cobol andAda are promoted by technical experts for use in writing votingautomation software, but vendors and some election officials claimthis would add to costs by requiring the conversion of existingassembly language systems.andP;  The FEC compromised on this andseveral other issues in the standards, which seven states havethus far incorporated.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Government AgencyNational GovernmentElectionsAutomationSoftware DesignSystem DesignStandardsUnited States. Federal Election Commission.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>